# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rlhf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:rlhf/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] A **Markov decision process** (**MDP**) is a mathematical model for sequential decision making when outcomes are uncertain.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] It is a type of stochastic decision process, and is often solved using the methods of stochastic dynamic programming.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Originating from operations research in the 1950s, MDPs have since gained recognition in a variety of fields, including ecology, economics, healthcare, telecommunications and reinforcement learning.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning utilizes the MDP framework to model the interaction between a learning agent and its environment.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In this framework, the interaction is characterized by states, actions, and rewards.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The MDP framework is designed to provide a simplified representation of key elements of artificial intelligence challenges.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] This modeling framework incorporates the understanding of cause and effect, the management of uncertainty and nondeterminism, and the pursuit of explicit goals.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The name comes from its connection to Markov chains, a concept developed by the Russian mathematician Andrey Markov.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The "Markov" in "Markov decision process" refers to the underlying structure of state transitions that still follow the Markov property.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The process is called a "decision process" because it involves making decisions that influence these state transitions, extending the concept of a Markov chain into the realm of decision-making under uncertainty.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] A policy function $\pi$ is a (potentially probabilistic) mapping from state space ( S ) to action space ( A ).
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The goal in a Markov decision process is to find a good "policy" for the decision maker: a function $\pi$ that specifies the action $\pi (s)$ that the decision maker will choose when in state s .
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Once a Markov decision process is combined with a policy in this way, this fixes the action for each state and the resulting combination behaves like a Markov chain (since the action chosen in state s is completely determined by $\pi (s)$ ).
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] where $\ \gamma \$ is the discount factor satisfying $0\leq \ \gamma \ \leq \ 1$ , which is usually close to 1 (for example, $\gamma =1/(1+r)$ for some discount rate r ).
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] A lower discount factor makes the decision maker more short-sighted, in that it comparatively disregards the effect that following its current policy has at times lying further in the future.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Another possible, but strictly related, objective that is commonly used is the $H-$ step return.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] This time, instead of using a discount factor $\ \gamma \$ , the agent is interested only in the first H steps of the process, with each reward having the same weight.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Compared to the previous objective, the latter one is more used in Learning Theory.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] A policy that maximizes the function above is called an **optimal policy** and is usually denoted $\pi ^{*}$ .
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] A particular MDP may have multiple distinct optimal policies.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Because of the Markov property, it can be shown that the optimal policy is a function of the current state, as assumed above.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] When $R_{a}(s,s')$ is deterministic, there will always exist an optimal policy $\pi ^{*}$ which is deterministic as well.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Assume that R is deterministic, meaning for constants $a,s,s'$ the value $R_{a}(s,s')$ is also constant.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] From inspection, notice that this fixed point is the value function associated to the following policy.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] By unrolling the Bellman recursion, one can show that $V^{*}$ is indeed optimal (simultaneously for all states) over the set of deterministic policies.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Consider the case where $\pi$ is probabilistic, meaning the action taken $a:=\pi (s)$ is a random variable.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] One can show any such non-deterministic policy is dominated by deterministic $\pi ^{*}$ as follows.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In many cases, it is difficult to represent the transition probability distributions, $P_{a}(s,s')$ , explicitly.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In such cases, a simulator can be used to model the MDP implicitly by providing samples from the transition distributions.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] One common form of implicit MDP model is an episodic environment simulator that can be started from an initial state and yields a subsequent state and reward every time it receives an action input.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In this manner, trajectories of states, actions, and rewards, often called **episodes** may be produced.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Another form of simulator is a **generative model**, a single step simulator that can generate samples of the next state and reward given any state and action.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] (Note that this is a different meaning from the term generative model in the context of statistical classification.) In algorithms that are expressed using pseudocode, G is often used to represent a generative model.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] For example, the expression $s',r\gets G(s,a)$ might denote the action of sampling from the generative model where s and a are the current state and action, and $s'$ and r are the new state and reward.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Compared to an episodic simulator, a generative model has the advantage that it can yield data from any state, not only those encountered in a trajectory.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] These model classes form a hierarchy of information content: an explicit model trivially yields a generative model through sampling from the distributions, and repeated application of a generative model yields an episodic simulator.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In the opposite direction, it is only possible to learn approximate models through regression.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The type of model available for a particular MDP plays a significant role in determining which solution algorithms are appropriate.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] An example of MDP is the Pole-Balancing model, which comes from classic control theory.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Solutions for MDPs with finite state and action spaces may be found through a variety of methods such as dynamic programming.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The algorithms in this section apply to MDPs with finite state and action spaces and explicitly given transition probabilities and reward functions, but the basic concepts may be extended to handle other problem classes, for example using function approximation.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Also, some processes with countably infinite state and action spaces can be *exactly* reduced to ones with finite state and action spaces.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The standard family of algorithms to calculate optimal policies for finite state and action MDPs requires storage for two arrays indexed by state: *value* V , which contains real values, and *policy* $\pi$ , which contains actions.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] At the end of the algorithm, $\pi$ will contain the solution and $V(s)$ will contain the discounted sum of the rewards to be earned (on average) by following that solution from state s .
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The algorithm has two steps, (1) a value update and (2) a policy update, which are repeated in some order for all the states until no further changes take place.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Both recursively update a new estimation of the optimal policy and state value using an older estimation of those values.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Their order depends on the variant of the algorithm; one can also do them for all states at once or state by state, and more often to some states than others.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] As long as no state is permanently excluded from either of the steps, the algorithm will eventually arrive at the correct solution.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In value iteration (Bellman 1957), which is also called backward induction, the $\pi$ function is not used; instead, the value of $\pi (s)$ is calculated within $V(s)$ whenever it is needed.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Value iteration starts at $i=0$ and $V_{0}$ as a guess of the value function.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] It then iterates, repeatedly computing $V_{i+1}$ for all states s , until V converges with the left-hand side equal to the right-hand side (which is the "Bellman equation" for this problem).
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Lloyd Shapley's 1953 paper on stochastic games included as a special case the value iteration method for MDPs, but this was recognized only later on.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Value iteration is guaranteed to converge for $\gamma <1$ by the Banach fixed-point theorem.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The Banach fixed-point theorem states that a given contraction mapping has a unique fixed point; further, one can asymptotically approach this fixed points by iterated application of the contraction mapping.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] It then suffices to show that value iteration is a contraction mapping, which is shown below for $\gamma <1$ .
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In policy iteration, one first performs *Value Determination* by solving for V from the linear system described in step one, then performs *Policy Improvement* by computing $\pi$ as in step two, then repeats both steps until the policy converges.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Since policy iteration effectively interleaves a linear inverse problem with a nonlinear operation, it may interpreted as a type of relaxation method.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] This variant has the advantage that there is a definite stopping condition.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Since there is a unique solution V for each policy $\pi$ , the algorithm is completed once the *Policy Improvement* produces the same policy twice consecutively.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] While there are situations where policy iteration may be faster than value iteration (e.g. when the action space is significantly larger than the state space), policy iteration is usually slower than value iteration for a large number of possible states.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In modified policy iteration (van Nunen 1976; Puterman & Shin 1978), step one is repeated several times, and then step two is performed once.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Then step one is again repeated several times and so on.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Algorithms for finding optimal policies with time complexity polynomial in the size of the problem representation exist for finite MDPs.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Thus, decision problems based on MDPs are in computational complexity class P.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] However, due to the curse of dimensionality, the size of the problem representation is often exponential in the number of state and action variables, limiting exact solution techniques to problems that have a compact representation.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] A Markov decision process is a stochastic game with only one player.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The solution above assumes that the state s is known when action is to be taken; otherwise $\pi (s)$ cannot be calculated.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] When this assumption is not true, the problem is called a partially observable Markov decision process or POMDP.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Constrained Markov decision processes (CMDPS) are extensions to Markov decision process (MDPs).
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] There are three fundamental differences between MDPs and CMDPs.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The method of Lagrange multipliers applies to CMDPs.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Many Lagrangian-based algorithms have been developed.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] There are a number of applications for CMDPs.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] It has recently been used in motion planning scenarios in robotics.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In discrete-time Markov Decision Processes, decisions are made at discrete time intervals.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] However, for **continuous-time Markov decision processes**, decisions can be made at any time the decision maker chooses.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In comparison to discrete-time Markov decision processes, continuous-time Markov decision processes can better model the decision-making process for a system that has continuous dynamics, i.e., the system dynamics are defined by ordinary differential equations (ODEs).
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] This modelling framework can be applied to areas such as queueing systems, epidemic processes, and population processes.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Like the discrete-time Markov decision processes, in continuous-time Markov decision processes the agent aims to find the optimal *policy* that would maximize the expected cumulative reward.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] If the state space and action space are finite, we could use linear programming to find the optimal policy, which was one of the earliest approaches applied.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Here we only consider the ergodic model, which means our continuous-time MDP becomes an ergodic continuous-time Markov chain under a stationary policy.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Under this assumption, although the decision maker can make a decision at any time in the current state, there is no benefit in taking multiple actions.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] It is better to take an action only at the time when system is transitioning from the current state to another state.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] If there exists a function h , then ${\bar {V}}^{*}$ will be the smallest g satisfying the above equation.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] $y(i,a)$ is a feasible solution to the D-LP if $y(i,a)$ is nonnative and satisfied the constraints in the D-LP problem.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] for all feasible solution $y(i,a)$ to the D-LP.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Once we have found the optimal solution $y^{*}(i,a)$ , we can use it to establish the optimal policies.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In continuous-time MDP, if the state space and action space are continuous, the optimal criterion could be found by solving the Hamilton–Jacobi–Bellman (HJB) partial differential equation.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] $D(\cdot )$ is the terminal reward function, $s(t)$ is the system state vector, $a(t)$ is the system control vector we try to find. $f(\cdot )$ shows how the state vector changes over time.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning is an interdisciplinary area of machine learning and optimal control that has, as main objective, finding an approximately optimal policy for MDPs where transition probabilities and rewards are unknown.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning can solve Markov-Decision processes without explicit specification of the transition probabilities which are instead needed to perform policy iteration.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In this setting, transition probabilities and rewards must be learned from experience, i.e. by letting an agent interact with the MDP for a given number of steps.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] While this function is also unknown, experience during learning is based on $(s,a)$ pairs (together with the outcome $s'$ ; that is, "I was in state s and I tried doing a and $s'$ happened").
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Thus, one has an array Q and uses experience to update it directly.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Another application of MDP process in machine learning theory is called learning automata.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] This is also one type of reinforcement learning if the environment is stochastic.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The first detail **learning automata** paper is surveyed by Narendra and Thathachar (1974), which were originally described explicitly as finite-state automata.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Similar to reinforcement learning, a learning automata algorithm also has the advantage of solving the problem when probability or rewards are unknown.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The difference between learning automata and Q-learning is that the former technique omits the memory of Q-values, but updates the action probability directly to find the learning result.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Learning automata is a learning scheme with a rigorous proof of convergence.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The states of such an automaton correspond to the states of a "discrete-state discrete-parameter Markov process".
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] At each time step *t* = 0,1,2,3,..., the automaton reads an input from its environment, updates P(*t*) to P(*t* + 1) by *A*, randomly chooses a successor state according to the probabilities P(*t* + 1) and outputs the corresponding action.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The automaton's environment, in turn, reads the action and sends the next input to the automaton.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Other than the rewards, a Markov decision process $(S,A,P)$ can be understood in terms of Category theory.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Namely, let ${\mathcal {A}}$ denote the free monoid with generating set *A*.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Let **Dist** denote the Kleisli category of the Giry monad.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] Then a functor ${\mathcal {A}}\to \mathbf {Dist}$ encodes both the set *S* of states and the probability function *P*.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In this way, Markov decision processes could be generalized from monoids (categories with one object) to arbitrary categories.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] One can call the result $({\mathcal {C}},F:{\mathcal {C}}\to \mathbf {Dist} )$ a *context-dependent Markov decision process*, because moving from one object to another in ${\mathcal {C}}$ changes the set of available actions and the set of possible states.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] The terminology and notation for MDPs are not entirely settled.
[src:rlhf/markov-decision-process] In addition, the notation for the transition probability varies.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The predecessor to PPO, Trust Region Policy Optimization (TRPO), was published in 2015.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] It addressed the instability issue of another algorithm, the Deep Q-Network (DQN), by using the trust region method to limit the KL divergence between the old and new policies.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] However, TRPO uses the Hessian matrix (a matrix of second derivatives) to enforce the trust region, but the Hessian is inefficient for large-scale problems.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] It was essentially an approximation of TRPO that does not require computing the Hessian.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The KL divergence constraint was approximated by simply clipping the policy gradient.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Since 2018, PPO was the default RL algorithm at OpenAI.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] PPO has been applied to many areas, such as controlling a robotic arm, beating professional players at Dota 2 (OpenAI Five), and playing Atari games.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] TRPO, the predecessor of PPO, is an on-policy algorithm.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] It can be used for environments with either discrete or continuous action spaces.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Like all policy gradient methods, PPO is used for training an RL agent whose actions are determined by a differentiable policy function by gradient ascent.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Intuitively, a policy gradient method takes small policy update steps, so the agent can reach higher and higher rewards in expectation.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Policy gradient methods may be unstable: A step size that is too big may direct the policy in a suboptimal direction, thus having little possibility of recovery; a step size that is too small lowers the overall efficiency.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] To solve the instability, PPO implements a *clip function* that constrains the policy update of an agent from being too large, so that larger step sizes may be used without negatively affecting the gradient ascent process.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] To begin the PPO training process, the agent is set in an environment to perform actions based on its current input.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] In the early phase of training, the agent can freely explore solutions and keep track of the result.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Later, with a certain amount of transition samples and policy updates, the agent will select an action to take by randomly sampling from the probability distribution $P(A|S)$ generated by the policy network.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The actions that are most likely to be beneficial will have the highest probability of being selected from the random sample.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] After an agent arrives at a different scenario (a new state) by acting, it is rewarded with a positive reward or a negative reward.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The objective of an agent is to maximize the cumulative reward signal across sequences of states, known as *episodes*.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The *advantage function* (denoted as A ) is central to PPO, as it tries to answer the question of whether a specific action of the agent is better or worse than some other possible action in a given state.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] By definition, the advantage function is an estimate of the relative value for a selected action.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] If the output of this function is positive, it means that the action in question is better than the average return, so the possibilities of selecting that specific action will increase.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The opposite is true for a negative advantage output.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The advantage function can be defined as $A=Q-V$ , where Q is the discounted sum of rewards (the total weighted reward for the completion of an episode) and V is the baseline estimate.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Since the advantage function is calculated after the completion of an episode, the program records the outcome of the episode.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Therefore, calculating advantage is essentially an unsupervised learning problem.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The baseline estimate comes from the value function that outputs the *expected* discounted sum of an episode starting from the current state.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] In the PPO algorithm, the baseline estimate will be noisy (with some variance), as it also uses a neural network, like the policy function itself.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] With Q and V computed, the advantage function is calculated by subtracting the baseline estimate from the actual discounted return.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] If $A>0$ , the actual return of the action is better than the expected return from experience; if $A<0$ , the actual return is worse.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] In PPO, the *ratio function* ( $r_{t}$ ) calculates the probability of selecting action a in state s given the current policy network, divided by the previous probability under the old policy.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Hence, this ratio function can easily estimate the divergence between old and current policies.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The objective function of PPO takes the expectation operator (denoted as E ) which means that this function will be computed over quantities of trajectories.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] 2. $\operatorname {clip} (r_{t}(\theta ))\cdot A$ : the policy ratio is first clipped to the range $[1-\epsilon ,1+\epsilon ]$ ; generally, $\epsilon$ is defined to be 0.2.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Then, as before, it is multiplied by the advantage.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The fundamental intuition behind PPO is the same as that of TRPO: conservatism.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Clipping results in a conservative advantage estimate of the new policy.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The reasoning is that if an agent makes significant changes due to high advantage estimates, its policy update will be large and unstable, and may diverge from the optimal policy with little possibility of recovery.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] There are two common applications of the clipping function: when an action under a new policy happens to be a good choice based on the advantage function, the clipping function limits how much credit can be given to a new policy for up-weighted good actions.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] On the other hand, when an action under the old policy is judged to be bad, the clipping function constrains how much the agent can accept the down-weighted bad actions of the new policy.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Consequently, the clipping mechanism is designed to discourage the incentive of moving beyond the defined range by clipping both directions.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The advantage of this method is that it can be optimized directly with gradient descent, as opposed to the strict KL divergence constraint of TRPO, making the implementation faster and more intuitive.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] After computing the clipped surrogate objective function, the agent has two probability ratios: one non-clipped and one clipped.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Then, by taking the minimum of the two objectives, the final objective becomes a lower bound (a *pessimistic* bound) of what the agent knows is possible.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] In other words, the minimum method makes sure that the agent is doing the safest possible update.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] PPO approximates what TRPO does, with considerably less computation.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] It uses first-order optimization (the clip function) to constrain the policy update, while TRPO uses KL divergence constraints (second-order optimization).
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Compared to TRPO, the PPO method is relatively easy to implement and requires less computational resource and time.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Therefore, it is cheaper and more efficient to use PPO in large-scale problems.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] While other RL algorithms require hyperparameter tuning, PPO comparatively does not require as much (0.2 for epsilon can be used in most cases).
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Also, PPO does not require sophisticated optimization techniques.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] It can be easily practiced with standard deep learning frameworks and generalized to a broad range of tasks.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Sample efficiency indicates whether the algorithms need more or less data to train a good policy.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] PPO achieved sample efficiency because of its use of surrogate objectives.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] The surrogate objective allows PPO to avoid the new policy moving too far from the old policy; the clip function regularizes the policy update and reuses training data.
[src:rlhf/proximal-policy-optimization] Sample efficiency is especially useful for complicated and high-dimensional tasks, where data collection and computation can be costly.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] For example, in a grid maze, an agent learns to reach an exit worth 10 points.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] At a junction, Q-learning might assign a higher value to moving right than left if right gets to the exit faster, improving this choice by trying both directions over time.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] For any finite Markov decision process, *Q*-learning finds an optimal policy in the sense of maximizing the expected value of the total reward over any and all successive steps, starting from the current state.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] *Q*-learning can identify an optimal action-selection policy for any given finite Markov decision process, given infinite exploration time and a partly random policy.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] "Q" refers to the function that the algorithm computes: the expected reward—that is, the *quality*—of an action taken in a given state.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Reinforcement learning involves an agent, a set of *states* ${\mathcal {S}}$ , and a set ${\mathcal {A}}$ of *actions* per state.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] By performing an action $a\in {\mathcal {A}}$ , the agent transitions from state to state.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Executing an action in a specific state provides the agent with a *reward* (a numerical score).
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The goal of the agent is to maximize its total reward.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] It does this by adding the maximum reward attainable from future states to the reward for achieving its current state, effectively influencing the current action by the potential future reward.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] This potential reward is a weighted sum of expected values of the rewards of all future steps starting from the current state.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] As an example, consider the process of boarding a train, in which the reward is measured by the negative of the total time spent boarding (alternatively, the cost of boarding the train is equal to the boarding time).
[src:rlhf/q-learning] One strategy is to enter the train door as soon as they open, minimizing the initial wait time for yourself.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] If the train is crowded, however, then you will have a slow entry after the initial action of entering the door as people are fighting you to depart the train as you attempt to board.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] On the next day, by random chance (exploration), you decide to wait and let other people depart first.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] This initially results in a longer wait time.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] However, less time is spent fighting the departing passengers.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Through exploration, despite the initial (patient) action resulting in a larger cost (or negative reward) than in the forceful strategy, the overall cost is lower, thus revealing a more rewarding strategy.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] After $\Delta t$ steps into the future the agent will decide some next step.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The weight for this step is calculated as $\gamma ^{\Delta t}$ , where $\gamma$ (the *discount factor*) is a number between 0 and 1 ( $0\leq \gamma \leq 1$ ).
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Assuming $\gamma <1$ , it has the effect of valuing rewards received earlier higher than those received later (reflecting the value of a "good start"). $\gamma$ may also be interpreted as the probability to succeed (or survive) at every step $\Delta t$ .
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Before learning begins, ⁠ Q ⁠ is initialized to a possibly arbitrary fixed value (chosen by the programmer).
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Then, at each time t the agent selects an action $A_{t}$ , observes a reward $R_{t+1}$ , enters a new state $S_{t+1}$ (that may depend on both the previous state $S_{t}$ and the selected action), and Q is updated.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] where *$R_{t+1}$* is the reward received when moving from the state $S_{t}$ to the state $S_{t+1}$ , and $\alpha$ is the learning rate $(0<\alpha \leq 1)$ .
[src:rlhf/q-learning] An episode of the algorithm ends when state $S_{t+1}$ is a final or *terminal state*.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] However, *Q*-learning can also learn in non-episodic tasks (as a result of the property of convergent infinite series).
[src:rlhf/q-learning] If the discount factor is lower than 1, the action values are finite even if the problem can contain infinite loops or paths.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] For all final states $s_{f}$ , $Q(s_{f},a)$ is never updated, but is set to the reward value r observed for state $s_{f}$ .
[src:rlhf/q-learning] In most cases, $Q(s_{f},a)$ can be taken to equal zero.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The learning rate or *step size* determines to what extent newly acquired information overrides old information.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] A factor of 0 makes the agent learn nothing (exclusively exploiting prior knowledge), while a factor of 1 makes the agent consider only the most recent information (ignoring prior knowledge to explore possibilities).
[src:rlhf/q-learning] In fully deterministic environments, a learning rate of $\alpha _{t}=1$ is optimal.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] When the problem is stochastic, the algorithm converges under some technical conditions on the learning rate that require it to decrease to zero.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] In practice, often a constant learning rate is used, such as $\alpha _{t}=0.1$ for all t .
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The discount factor ⁠ $\gamma$ ⁠ determines the importance of future rewards.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] A factor of 0 will make the agent "myopic" (or short-sighted) by only considering current rewards, i.e. $r_{t}$ (in the update rule above), while a factor approaching 1 will make it strive for a long-term high reward.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] If the discount factor meets or exceeds 1, the action values may diverge.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] For ⁠ $\gamma =1$ ⁠, without a terminal state, or if the agent never reaches one, all environment histories become infinitely long, and utilities with additive, undiscounted rewards generally become infinite.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Even with a discount factor only slightly lower than 1, *Q*-function learning leads to propagation of errors and instabilities when the value function is approximated with an artificial neural network.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] In that case, starting with a lower discount factor and increasing it towards its final value accelerates learning.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Since *Q*-learning is an iterative algorithm, it implicitly assumes an initial condition before the first update occurs.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] High initial values, also known as "optimistic initial conditions", can encourage exploration: no matter what action is selected, the update rule will cause it to have lower values than the other alternative, thus increasing their choice probability.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The first reward r can be used to reset the initial conditions.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] According to this idea, the first time an action is taken the reward is used to set the value of Q .
[src:rlhf/q-learning] This allows immediate learning in case of fixed deterministic rewards.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] A model that incorporates *reset of initial conditions* (RIC) is expected to predict participants' behavior better than a model that assumes any *arbitrary initial condition* (AIC).
[src:rlhf/q-learning] RIC seems to be consistent with human behaviour in repeated binary choice experiments.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] One solution is to use an (adapted) artificial neural network as a function approximator.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Another possibility is to integrate Fuzzy Rule Interpolation (FRI) and use sparse fuzzy rule-bases instead of discrete Q-tables or ANNs, which has the advantage of being a human-readable knowledge representation form.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Function approximation may speed up learning in finite problems, due to the fact that the algorithm can generalize earlier experiences to previously unseen states.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Another technique to decrease the state/action space quantizes possible values.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Consider the example of learning to balance a stick on a finger.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] To describe a state at a certain point in time involves the position of the finger in space, its velocity, the angle of the stick and the angular velocity of the stick.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] This yields a four-element vector that describes one state, i.e. a snapshot of one state encoded into four values.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The problem is that infinitely many possible states are present.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] To shrink the possible space of valid actions multiple values can be assigned to a bucket.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The exact distance of the finger from its starting position (-Infinity to Infinity) is not known, but rather whether it is far away or not (Near, Far).
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The term "secondary reinforcement" is borrowed from animal learning theory, to model state values via backpropagation: the state value ⁠ $v(s')$ ⁠ of the consequence situation is backpropagated to the previously encountered situations.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] CAA computes state values vertically and actions horizontally (the "crossbar").
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Demonstration graphs showing delayed reinforcement learning contained states (desirable, undesirable, and neutral states), which were computed by the state evaluation function.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] This learning system was a forerunner of the Q-learning algorithm.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] In 2014, Google DeepMind patented an application of Q-learning to deep learning, entitled "deep reinforcement learning" or "deep Q-learning," that can play Atari 2600 games at expert human levels.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The DeepMind system used a deep convolutional neural network, with layers of tiled convolutional filters to mimic the effects of receptive fields.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Reinforcement learning is unstable or divergent when a nonlinear function approximator such as a neural network is used to represent Q.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] This instability comes from the correlations present in the sequence of observations, the fact that small updates to Q may significantly change the policy of the agent and the data distribution, and the correlations between Q and the target values.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The method can be used for stochastic search in various domains and applications.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The technique used *experience replay,* a biologically inspired mechanism that uses a random sample of prior actions instead of the most recent action to proceed.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] This removes correlations in the observation sequence and smooths changes in the data distribution.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Iterative updates adjust Q towards target values that are only periodically updated, further reducing correlations with the target.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Because the future maximum approximated action value in Q-learning is evaluated using the same Q function as in current action selection policy, in noisy environments Q-learning can sometimes overestimate the action values, slowing the learning.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] A variant called Double Q-learning was proposed to correct this.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Double Q-learning is an off-policy reinforcement learning algorithm, where a different policy is used for value evaluation than what is used to select the next action.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] In practice, two separate value functions $Q^{A}$ and $Q^{B}$ are trained in a mutually symmetric fashion using separate experiences.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Now the estimated value of the discounted future is evaluated using a different policy, which solves the overestimation issue.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] This algorithm was later modified in 2015 and combined with deep learning, as in the DQN algorithm, resulting in Double DQN, which outperforms the original DQN algorithm.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Delayed Q-learning is an alternative implementation of the online *Q*-learning algorithm, with probably approximately correct (PAC) learning.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Greedy GQ is a variant of *Q*-learning to use in combination with (linear) function approximation.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The advantage of Greedy GQ is that convergence is guaranteed even when function approximation is used to estimate the action values.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Distributional Q-learning is a variant of *Q*-learning which seeks to model the distribution of returns rather than the expected return of each action.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] It has been observed to facilitate estimate by deep neural networks and can enable alternative control methods, such as risk-sensitive control.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Q-learning has been proposed in the multi-agent setting (see Section 4.1.2 in ).
[src:rlhf/q-learning] One approach consists in pretending the environment is passive.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Littman proposes the minimax Q learning algorithm.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] The standard Q-learning algorithm (using a Q table) applies only to discrete action and state spaces.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] Discretization of these values leads to inefficient learning, largely due to the curse of dimensionality.
[src:rlhf/q-learning] However, there are adaptations of Q-learning that attempt to solve this problem such as Wire-fitted Neural Network Q-Learning.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In machine learning, **reinforcement learning from human feedback** (**RLHF**) is a technique to align an intelligent agent with human preferences.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It involves training a reward model to represent preferences, which can then be used to train other models through reinforcement learning.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In classical reinforcement learning, an intelligent agent's goal is to learn a function that guides its behavior, called a policy.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The function is iteratively optimized to increase the reward signal derived from the agent's task performance.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] However, explicitly defining a reward function that accurately approximates human preferences is challenging.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Therefore, RLHF seeks to train a "reward model" directly from human feedback.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The reward model is first trained in a supervised manner to predict if a response to a given prompt is good (high reward) or bad (low reward) based on ranking data collected from human annotators.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This model then serves as a reward function to improve an agent's policy through an optimization algorithm like proximal policy optimization.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF has applications in various domains in machine learning, including natural language processing tasks such as text summarization and conversational agents, computer vision tasks like text-to-image models, and the development of video game bots.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] While RLHF is an effective method of training models to act better in accordance with human preferences, it also faces challenges due to the way the human preference data is collected.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Though RLHF does not require massive amounts of data to improve performance, sourcing high-quality preference data is still an expensive process.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Furthermore, if the data is not carefully collected from a representative sample, the resulting model may exhibit unwanted biases.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Optimizing a model based on human feedback is desirable when a task is difficult to specify yet easy to judge.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] For example, one may want to train a model to generate safe text that is both helpful and harmless (such as lacking bias, toxicity, or otherwise harmful content).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Asking humans to manually create examples of harmless and harmful text would be difficult and time-consuming.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] However, humans are adept at swiftly assessing and comparing the harmfulness of different AI-generated text.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Therefore, a more practical objective would be to allow the model to use this type of human feedback to improve its text generation.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Despite the clear benefits of incorporating human feedback in training models, prior efforts—including some that leverage reinforcement learning (RL)—have encountered significant challenges.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Most attempts were either narrow and difficult to generalize, breaking down on more complex tasks, or they faced difficulties learning from sparse (lacking specific information and relating to large amounts of text at a time) or noisy (inconsistently rewarding similar outputs) reward functions.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF was not the first successful method of using human feedback for reinforcement learning, but it is one of the most widely used.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The foundation for RLHF was introduced as an attempt to create a general algorithm for learning from a practical amount of human feedback.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The algorithm as used today was introduced by OpenAI in a paper on enhancing text continuation or summarization based on human feedback, and it began to gain popularity when the same method was reused in their paper on InstructGPT.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF has also been shown to improve the robustness of RL agents and their capacity for exploration, which results in an optimization process more adept at handling uncertainty and efficiently exploring its environment in search of the highest reward.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Human feedback is commonly collected by prompting humans to rank instances of the agent's behavior.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] These rankings can then be used to score outputs, for example, using the Elo rating system, which is an algorithm for calculating the relative skill levels of players in a game based only on the outcome of each game.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] While ranking outputs is the most widely adopted form of feedback, recent research has explored other forms, such as numerical feedback, natural language feedback, and prompting for direct edits to the model's output.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] One initial motivation of RLHF was that it requires relatively small amounts of comparison data to be effective.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It has been shown that a small amount of data can lead to comparable results to a larger amount.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In addition, increasing the amount of data tends to be less effective than proportionally increasing the size of the reward model.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Nevertheless, a larger and more diverse amount of data can be crucial for tasks where it is important to avoid bias from a partially representative group of annotators.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This implies that, under certain conditions, if a model is trained to decide which choices people would prefer between pairs (or groups) of choices, it will necessarily improve at predicting future preferences.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This improvement is expected as long as the comparisons it learns from are based on a consistent and simple rule.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In the offline data collection model, when the objective is policy training, a pessimistic MLE that incorporates a lower confidence bound as the reward estimate is most effective.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Moreover, when applicable, it has been shown that considering K-wise comparisons directly is asymptotically more efficient than converting them into pairwise comparisons for prediction purposes.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] A key challenge in RLHF when learning from pairwise (or dueling) comparisons is associated with the non-Markovian nature of its optimal policies.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Unlike simpler scenarios where the optimal strategy does not require memory of past actions, in RLHF, the best course of action often depends on previous events and decisions, making the strategy inherently memory-dependent.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF has been applied to various domains of natural language processing (NLP), such as conversational agents, text summarization, and natural language understanding.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Ordinary reinforcement learning, in which agents learn from their actions based on a predefined "reward function", is difficult to apply to NLP tasks because the rewards tend to be difficult to define or measure, especially when dealing with complex tasks that involve human values or preferences.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF can steer NLP models, in particular language models, to provide answers that align with human preferences with regard to such tasks by capturing their preferences beforehand in the reward model.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This results in a model capable of generating more relevant responses and rejecting inappropriate or irrelevant queries.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Some notable examples of RLHF-trained language models are OpenAI's ChatGPT (and its predecessor InstructGPT), DeepMind's Sparrow, Google's Gemini, and Anthropic's Claude.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In computer vision, RLHF has also been used to align text-to-image models.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Studies that successfully used RLHF for this goal have noted that the use of KL regularization in RLHF, which aims to prevent the learned policy from straying too far from the unaligned model, helped to stabilize the training process by reducing overfitting to the reward model.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The final image outputs from models trained with KL regularization were noted to be of significantly higher quality than those trained without.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF was initially applied to other areas, such as the development of video game bots and tasks in simulated robotics.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] For example, OpenAI and DeepMind trained agents to play Atari games based on human preferences.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In classical RL-based training of such bots, the reward function is simply correlated to how well the agent is performing in the game, usually using metrics like the in-game score.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In comparison, in RLHF, a human is periodically presented with two clips of the agent's behavior in the game and must decide which one *looks* better.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This approach can teach agents to perform at a competitive level without ever having access to their score.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In fact, it was shown that RLHF can sometimes lead to superior performance over RL with score metrics because the human's preferences can contain more useful information than performance-based metrics.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The agents achieved strong performance in many of the environments tested, often surpassing human performance.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In RLHF, two different models are trained: a reward model and a reinforcement learning policy.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The reward model learns to determine what behavior is desirable based on human feedback, while the policy is guided by the reward model to determine the agent's actions.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Both models are commonly initialized using a pre-trained autoregressive language model.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This model is then customarily trained in a supervised manner on a relatively small dataset of pairs of prompts to an assistant and their accompanying responses, written by human annotators.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The **reward model** is a function that takes a string (piece of text) as input, and produces a single number, which is the "reward".
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It is usually initialized with a pre-trained model, as this initializes it with an understanding of language and focuses training explicitly on learning human preferences.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In addition to being used to initialize the reward model and the RL policy, the model is then also used to sample data to be compared by annotators.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The reward model is then trained by replacing the final layer of the previous model with a randomly initialized regression head.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This change shifts the model from its original classification task over its vocabulary to simply outputting a number corresponding to the score of any given prompt and response.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This model is trained on the human preference comparison data collected earlier from the supervised model.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] where K is the number of responses the labelers ranked, $r_{\theta }(x,y)$ is the output of the reward model for prompt x and completion y , $y_{w}$ is the preferred completion over $y_{l}$ , $\sigma (x)$ denotes the sigmoid function, and $E[X]$ denotes the expected value.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This can be thought of as a form of logistic regression, where the model predicts the probability that a response $y_{w}$ is preferred over $y_{l}$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This loss function essentially measures the difference between the reward model's predictions and the decisions made by humans.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The goal is to make the model's guesses as close as possible to the humans' preferences by minimizing the difference measured by this equation.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In the case of only pairwise comparisons, $K=2$ , so the factor of $1/{\tbinom {K}{2}}=1$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In general, all ${\tbinom {K}{2}}$ comparisons from each prompt are used for training as a single batch.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] After training, the outputs of the model are normalized such that the reference completions have a mean score of 0.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] That is, ${\textstyle \sum _{y}r_{\theta }(x,y)=0}$ for each query and reference pair $(x,y)$ by calculating the mean reward across the training dataset and setting it as the bias in the reward head.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The **policy model** is a function that takes a string as input, and produces another string.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Usually in language modeling, the output string is not produced in one forward pass, but by multiple forward passes, generated autoregressively.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Similarly to the reward model, the human feedback policy is also initialized from a pre-trained model.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The key is to understand language generation as if it is a game to be learned by RL.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In RL, a policy is a function that maps a game state to a game action.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In RLHF, the "game" is the game of replying to prompts.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] A prompt and all previously generated tokens are the game state, and generating a new token is a game action.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The first step in its training is supervised fine-tuning (SFT).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This step does not require the reward model.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Instead, the pre-trained model is trained on a dataset $D_{SFT}$ that contains prompt-response pairs $(x,y)$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Then, during SFT, the model is trained to auto-regressively generate the corresponding response y when given a random prompt x .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The original paper recommends to SFT for only one epoch, since more than that causes overfitting.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The dataset $D_{SFT}$ is usually written by human contractors, who write both the prompts and responses.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The second step uses a policy gradient method to the reward model.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It uses a dataset $D_{RL}$ , which contains prompts, but not responses.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Note that $(x,y)\sim D_{\pi _{\phi }^{\text{RL}}}$ is equivalent to $x\sim D_{RL},y\sim \pi _{\phi }^{\text{RL}}(\cdot |x)$ , which means "sample a prompt from $D_{RL}$ , then sample a response from the policy".
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The first part is simply the expected reward $E[r]$ , and is standard for any RL algorithm.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The second part is a "penalty term" involving the KL divergence.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The strength of the penalty term is determined by the hyperparameter $\beta$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This KL term works by penalizing the KL divergence (a measure of statistical distance between distributions) between the model being fine-tuned and the initial supervised model.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] By choosing an appropriate $\beta$ , the training can balance learning from new data while retaining useful information from the initial model, increasing generalization by avoiding fitting too closely to the new data.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Aside from preventing the new model from producing outputs too dissimilar those of the initial model, a second motivation of including the KL term is to encourage the model to output high-entropy text, so as to prevent the model from collapsing to a small number of canned responses.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In simpler terms, the objective function calculates how well the policy's responses are expected to align with human feedback.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The policy generates responses to prompts, and each response is evaluated both on how well it matches human preferences (as measured by the reward model) and how similar it is to responses the model would naturally generate.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The goal is to balance improving alignment with human preferences while ensuring the model's responses remain diverse and not too far removed from what it has learned during its initial training.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This helps the model not only to provide answers that people find useful or agreeable but also to maintain a broad understanding and avoid overly narrow or repetitive responses.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The policy function is usually trained by proximal policy optimization (PPO) algorithm.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] That is, the parameter $\phi$ is trained by gradient ascent on the clipped surrogate function.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The value estimator is used only during training, and not outside of training.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] That is, the advantage is computed as the difference between the reward (the expected return) and the value estimation (the expected return from the policy).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This is used to train the policy by gradient *ascent* on it, usually using a standard momentum-gradient optimizer, like the Adam optimizer.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The original paper initialized the value estimator from the trained reward model.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Other methods than squared TD-error might be used.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] See the actor-critic algorithm page for details.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] A third term is commonly added to the objective function to prevent the model from catastrophic forgetting.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] For example, if the model is only trained in customer service, then it might forget general knowledge in geography.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] To prevent this, the RLHF process incorporates the original language modeling objective.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] That is, some random texts x are sampled from the original pretraining dataset $D_{\text{pretrain}}$ , and the model is trained to maximize the log-likelihood of the text $\log(\pi _{\phi }^{RL}(x))$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] where $\gamma$ controls the strength of this pretraining term.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This combined objective function is called PPO-ptx, where "ptx" means "Mixing Pretraining Gradients".
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It was first used in the InstructGPT paper.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In total, this objective function defines the method for adjusting the RL policy, blending the aim of aligning with human feedback and maintaining the model's original language understanding.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF suffers from challenges with collecting human feedback, learning a reward model, and optimizing the policy.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Compared to data collection for techniques like unsupervised or self-supervised learning, collecting data for RLHF is less scalable and more expensive.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Its quality and consistency may vary depending on the task, interface, and the preferences and biases of individual humans.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The effectiveness of RLHF depends on the quality of human feedback.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] For instance, the model may become biased, favoring certain groups over others, if the feedback lacks impartiality, is inconsistent, or is incorrect.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] There is a risk of overfitting, where the model memorizes specific feedback examples instead of learning to generalize.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] For instance, feedback predominantly from a specific demographic might lead the model to learn peculiarities or noise, along with the intended alignment.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Excessive alignment to the specific feedback it received (that is, to the bias therein) can lead to the model performing sub-optimally in new contexts or when used by different groups.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] A single reward function cannot always represent the opinions of diverse groups of people.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Even with a representative sample, conflicting views and preferences may result in the reward model favoring the majority's opinion, potentially disadvantaging underrepresented groups.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In some cases, as is possible in regular reinforcement learning, there may be a risk of the model learning to manipulate the feedback process or game the system to achieve higher rewards rather than genuinely improving its performance.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In the case of RLHF, a model may learn to exploit the fact that it is rewarded for what is evaluated positively and not necessarily for what is actually good, which can lead to it learning to persuade and manipulate.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] For example, models might learn that apparent confidence, even if inaccurate, garners higher rewards.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Such behavior, if unchecked, is not just incentivized but can cause significant deployment issues due to the model's potential to mislead.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Studies have found that humans are not skilled at identifying mistakes in LLM outputs in complex tasks; therefore, models learning to generate confident-sounding yet incorrect text can lead to significant issues when deployed.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Similarly to RLHF, *reinforcement learning from AI feedback* (RLAIF) relies on training a preference model, except that the feedback is automatically generated.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This is notably used in Anthropic's constitutional AI, where the AI feedback is based on the conformance to the principles of a constitution.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Direct alignment algorithms (DAA) have been proposed as a new class of algorithms that seek to directly optimize large language models (LLMs) on human feedback data in a supervised manner instead of the traditional policy-gradient methods.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] These algorithms aim to align models with human intent more transparently by removing the intermediate step of training a separate reward model.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Instead of first predicting human preferences and then optimizing against those predictions, direct alignment methods train models end-to-end on human-labeled or curated outputs.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This reduces potential misalignment risks introduced by proxy objectives or reward hacking.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] By directly optimizing for the behavior preferred by humans, these approaches often enable tighter alignment with human values, improved interpretability, and simpler training pipelines compared to RLHF.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Direct preference optimization (DPO) is a technique to learn human preferences.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Like RLHF, it has been applied to align pre-trained large language models using human-generated preference data.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Unlike RLHF, however, which first trains a separate intermediate model to understand what good outcomes look like and then teaches the main model how to achieve those outcomes, DPO simplifies the process by directly adjusting the main model according to people's preferences.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It uses a change of variables to define the "preference loss" directly as a function of the policy and uses this loss to fine-tune the model, helping it understand and prioritize human preferences without needing a separate step.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Essentially, this approach directly shapes the model's decisions based on positive or negative human feedback.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] However, instead of doing the intermediate step of the reward model, DPO directly optimizes for the final policy.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Usually, DPO is used for modeling human preference in pairwise comparisons, so that $N=2$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] DPO eliminates the need for a separate reward model or reinforcement learning loop, treating alignment as a supervised learning problem over preference data.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This is simpler to implement and train than RLHF and has been shown to produce comparable and sometimes superior results.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Nevertheless, RLHF has also been shown to beat DPO on some datasets, for example, on benchmarks that attempt to measure truthfulness.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Therefore, the choice of method may vary depending on the features of the human preference data and the nature of the task.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Identity preference optimization (IPO) is a modification to the original DPO objective that introduces a regularization term to reduce the chance of overfitting even when preference data is noisy.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] IPO can control the gap between the log-likelihood ratios of the policy model and the reference by always regularizing the solution towards the reference model.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It allows learning directly from preferences without a reward modelling stage and without relying on the Bradley-Terry modelling assumption that assumes that pairwise preferences can be substituted with pointwise rewards.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Kahneman-Tversky optimization (KTO) is another direct alignment algorithm drawing from prospect theory to model uncertainty in human decisions.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Unlike DPO, KTO requires only a binary feedback signal (desirable or undesirable) instead of explicit preference pairs.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Since many real-world feedback pipelines yield "like/dislike" data more easily than pairwise comparisons, KTO is designed to be data-efficient and to reflect "loss aversion" more directly by using a straightforward notion of "good vs. bad" at the example level.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In machine learning and optimal control, **reinforcement learning** (**RL**) is concerned with how an intelligent agent should take actions in a dynamic environment in order to maximize a reward signal.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning is one of the three basic machine learning paradigms, alongside supervised learning and unsupervised learning.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] While supervised learning and unsupervised learning algorithms respectively attempt to discover patterns in labeled and unlabeled data, reinforcement learning involves training an agent through interactions with its environment.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] To learn to maximize rewards from these interactions, the agent makes decisions between trying new actions to learn more about the environment (exploration), or using current knowledge of the environment to take the best action (exploitation).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The search for the optimal balance between these two strategies is known as the exploration–exploitation dilemma.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The environment is typically stated in the form of a Markov decision process, as many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The main difference between classical dynamic programming methods and reinforcement learning algorithms is that the latter do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the Markov decision process, and they target large Markov decision processes where exact methods become infeasible.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Due to its generality, reinforcement learning is studied in many disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimization, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, and statistics.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The purpose of reinforcement learning is for the agent to learn an optimal (or near-optimal) policy that maximizes the reward function or other user-provided reinforcement signal that accumulates from immediate rewards.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This is similar to processes that appear to occur in animal psychology.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] For example, biological brains are hardwired to interpret signals such as pain and hunger as negative reinforcements, and interpret pleasure and food intake as positive reinforcements.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In some circumstances, animals learn to adopt behaviors that optimize these rewards.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This suggests that animals are capable of reinforcement learning.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] A basic reinforcement learning agent interacts with its environment in discrete time steps.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] At each time step t, the agent receives the current state $S_{t}$ and reward $R_{t}$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] It then chooses an action $A_{t}$ from the set of available actions, which is subsequently sent to the environment.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The environment moves to a new state $S_{t+1}$ and the reward $R_{t+1}$ associated with the *transition* $(S_{t},A_{t},S_{t+1})$ is determined.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] that maximizes the expected cumulative reward.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Formulating the problem as a Markov decision process assumes the agent directly observes the current environmental state; in this case, the problem is said to have *full observability*.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] If the agent only has access to a subset of states, or if the observed states are corrupted by noise, the agent is said to have *partial observability*, and formally the problem must be formulated as a partially observable Markov decision process.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In both cases, the set of actions available to the agent can be restricted.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] For example, the state of an account balance could be restricted to be positive; if the current value of the state is 3 and the state transition attempts to reduce the value by 4, the transition will not be allowed.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] When the agent's performance is compared to that of an agent that acts optimally, the difference in performance yields the notion of regret.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In order to act near optimally, the agent must reason about long-term consequences of its actions (i.e., maximize future rewards), although the immediate reward associated with this might be negative.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Thus, reinforcement learning is particularly well-suited to problems that include a long-term versus short-term reward trade-off.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] It has been applied successfully to various problems, including energy storage, robot control, photovoltaic generators, backgammon, checkers, Go (AlphaGo), and autonomous driving systems.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Two elements make reinforcement learning powerful: the use of samples to optimize performance, and the use of function approximation to deal with large environments.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The first two of these problems could be considered planning problems (since some form of model is available), while the last one could be considered to be a genuine learning problem.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] However, reinforcement learning converts both planning problems to machine learning problems.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The trade-off between exploration and exploitation has been most thoroughly studied through the multi-armed bandit problem and for finite state space Markov decision processes in Burnetas and Katehakis (1997).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning requires clever exploration mechanisms; randomly selecting actions, without reference to an estimated probability distribution, shows poor performance.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The case of (small) finite Markov decision processes is relatively well understood.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] However, due to the lack of algorithms that scale well with the number of states (or scale to problems with infinite state spaces), simple exploration methods are the most practical.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] One such method is $\varepsilon$ -greedy, where $0<\varepsilon <1$ is a parameter controlling the amount of exploration vs. exploitation.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] With probability $1-\varepsilon$ , exploitation is chosen, and the agent chooses the action that it believes has the best long-term effect (ties between actions are broken uniformly at random).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Alternatively, with probability $\varepsilon$ , exploration is chosen, and the action is chosen uniformly at random. $\varepsilon$ is usually a fixed parameter but can be adjusted either according to a schedule (making the agent explore progressively less), or adaptively based on heuristics.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Even if the issue of exploration is disregarded and even if the state was observable (assumed hereafter), the problem remains to use past experience to find out which actions lead to higher cumulative rewards.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The policy map gives the probability of taking action a when in state s .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] There are also deterministic policies $\pi$ for which $\pi (s)$ denotes the action that should be played at state s .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The state-value function $V_{\pi }(s)$ is defined as, *expected discounted return* starting with state s , i.e. $S_{0}=s$ , and successively following policy $\pi$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Hence, roughly speaking, the value function estimates "how good" it is to be in a given state.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] where $R_{t+1}$ is the reward for transitioning from state $S_{t}$ to $S_{t+1}$ , $0\leq \gamma <1$ is the discount rate. $\gamma$ is less than 1, so rewards in the distant future are weighted less than rewards in the immediate future.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The algorithm must find a policy with maximum expected discounted return.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] From the theory of Markov decision processes it is known that, without loss of generality, the search can be restricted to the set of so-called *stationary* policies.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] A policy is *stationary* if the action-distribution returned by it depends only on the last state visited (from the observation agent's history).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The search can be further restricted to *deterministic* stationary policies.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] A *deterministic stationary* policy deterministically selects actions based on the current state.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Since any such policy can be identified with a mapping from the set of states to the set of actions, these policies can be identified with such mappings with no loss of generality.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] One problem with this is that the number of policies can be large, or even infinite.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Another is that the variance of the returns may be large, which requires many samples to accurately estimate the discounted return of each policy.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] These problems can be ameliorated if we assume some structure and allow samples generated from one policy to influence the estimates made for others.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The two main approaches for achieving this are value function estimation and direct policy search.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Value function approaches attempt to find a policy that maximizes the discounted return by maintaining a set of estimates of expected discounted returns $\operatorname {\mathbb {E} } [G]$ for some policy (usually either the "current" [on-policy] or the optimal [off-policy] one).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] These methods rely on the theory of Markov decision processes, where optimality is defined in a sense stronger than the one above: A policy is optimal if it achieves the best-expected discounted return from *any* initial state (i.e., initial distributions play no role in this definition).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Again, an optimal policy can always be found among stationary policies.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] where G stands for the discounted return associated with following $\pi$ from the initial state s .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] A policy that achieves these optimal state-values in each state is called *optimal*.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Clearly, a policy that is optimal in this sense is also optimal in the sense that it maximizes the expected discounted return, since $V^{*}(s)=\max _{\pi }\mathbb {E} [G\mid s,\pi ]$ , where s is a state randomly sampled from the distribution $\mu$ of initial states (so $\mu (s)=\Pr(S_{0}=s)$ ).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Although state-values suffice to define optimality, it is useful to define action-values.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] where G now stands for the random discounted return associated with first taking action a in state s and following $\pi$ , thereafter.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The theory of Markov decision processes states that if $\pi ^{*}$ is an optimal policy, we act optimally (take the optimal action) by choosing the action from $Q^{\pi ^{*}}(s,\cdot )$ with the highest action-value at each state, s .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The *action-value function* of such an optimal policy ( $Q^{\pi ^{*}}$ ) is called the *optimal action-value function* and is commonly denoted by $Q^{*}$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In summary, the knowledge of the optimal action-value function alone suffices to know how to act optimally.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Assuming full knowledge of the Markov decision process, the two basic approaches to compute the optimal action-value function are value iteration and policy iteration.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Both algorithms compute a sequence of functions $Q_{k}$ ( $k=0,1,2,\ldots$ ) that converge to $Q^{*}$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Computing these functions involves computing expectations over the whole state-space, which is impractical for all but the smallest (finite) Markov decision processes.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In reinforcement learning methods, expectations are approximated by averaging over samples and using function approximation techniques to cope with the need to represent value functions over large state-action spaces.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Monte Carlo methods are used to solve reinforcement learning problems by averaging sample returns.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Unlike methods that require full knowledge of the environment's dynamics, Monte Carlo methods rely solely on actual or simulated experience—sequences of states, actions, and rewards obtained from interaction with an environment.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This makes them applicable in situations where the complete dynamics are unknown.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Learning from actual experience does not require prior knowledge of the environment and can still lead to optimal behavior.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] When using simulated experience, only a model capable of generating sample transitions is required, rather than a full specification of transition probabilities, which is necessary for dynamic programming methods.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Monte Carlo methods apply to episodic tasks, where experience is divided into episodes that eventually terminate.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Policy and value function updates occur only after the completion of an episode, making these methods incremental on an episode-by-episode basis, though not on a step-by-step (online) basis.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The term "Monte Carlo" generally refers to any method involving random sampling; however, in this context, it specifically refers to methods that compute averages from *complete* returns, rather than *partial* returns.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] These methods function similarly to the bandit algorithms, in which returns are averaged for each state-action pair.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The key difference is that actions taken in one state affect the returns of subsequent states within the same episode, making the problem non-stationary.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] To address this non-stationarity, Monte Carlo methods use the framework of general policy iteration (GPI).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] While dynamic programming computes value functions using full knowledge of the Markov decision process, Monte Carlo methods learn these functions through sample returns.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The value functions and policies interact similarly to dynamic programming to achieve optimality, first addressing the prediction problem and then extending to policy improvement and control, all based on sampled experience.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The first problem is corrected by allowing the procedure to change the policy (at some or all states) before the values settle.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This too may be problematic as it might prevent convergence.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Most current algorithms do this, giving rise to the class of *generalized policy iteration* algorithms.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Many *actor-critic* methods belong to this category.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The second issue can be corrected by allowing trajectories to contribute to any state-action pair in them.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This may also help to some extent with the third problem, although a better solution when returns have high variance is Sutton's temporal difference (TD) methods that are based on the recursive Bellman equation.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The computation in TD methods can be incremental (when after each transition the memory is changed and the transition is thrown away), or batch (when the transitions are batched and the estimates are computed once based on the batch).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Batch methods, such as the least-squares temporal difference method, may use the information in the samples better, while incremental methods are the only choice when batch methods are infeasible due to their high computational or memory complexity.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Some methods try to combine the two approaches.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Methods based on temporal differences also overcome the fourth issue.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Another problem specific to TD comes from their reliance on the recursive Bellman equation.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Most TD methods have a so-called $\lambda$ parameter $(0\leq \lambda \leq 1)$ that can continuously interpolate between Monte Carlo methods that do not rely on the Bellman equations and the basic TD methods that rely entirely on the Bellman equations.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This can be effective in palliating this issue.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In order to address the fifth issue, *function approximation methods* are used.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] *Linear function approximation* starts with a mapping $\phi$ that assigns a finite-dimensional vector to each state-action pair.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The algorithms then adjust the weights, instead of adjusting the values associated with the individual state-action pairs.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Methods based on ideas from nonparametric statistics (which can be seen to construct their own features) have been explored.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Value iteration can also be used as a starting point, giving rise to the Q-learning algorithm and its many variants.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Including Deep Q-learning methods when a neural network is used to represent Q, with various applications in stochastic search problems.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The problem with using action-values is that they may need highly precise estimates of the competing action values that can be hard to obtain when the returns are noisy, though this problem is mitigated to some extent by temporal difference methods.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Using the so-called compatible function approximation method compromises generality and efficiency.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] An alternative method is to search directly in (some subset of) the policy space, in which case the problem becomes a case of stochastic optimization.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The two approaches available are gradient-based and gradient-free methods.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Gradient-based methods (*policy gradient methods*) start with a mapping from a finite-dimensional (parameter) space to the space of policies: given the parameter vector $\theta$ , let $\pi _{\theta }$ denote the policy associated to $\theta$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Defining the performance function by $\rho (\theta )=\rho ^{\pi _{\theta }}$ under mild conditions this function will be differentiable as a function of the parameter vector $\theta$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] If the gradient of $\rho$ was known, one could use gradient ascent.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Since an analytic expression for the gradient is not available, only a noisy estimate is available.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Such an estimate can be constructed in many ways, giving rise to algorithms such as Williams's REINFORCE method (which is known as the likelihood ratio method in the simulation-based optimization literature).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] A large class of methods avoids relying on gradient information.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] These include simulated annealing, cross-entropy search or methods of evolutionary computation.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Many gradient-free methods can achieve (in theory and in the limit) a global optimum.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Policy search methods may converge slowly given noisy data.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] For example, this happens in episodic problems when the trajectories are long and the variance of the returns is large.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Value-function based methods that rely on temporal differences might help in this case.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In recent years, *actor–critic methods* have been proposed and performed well on various problems.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Policy search methods have been used in the robotics context.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Many policy search methods may get stuck in local optima (as they are based on local search).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Finally, all of the above methods can be combined with algorithms that first learn a model of the Markov decision process, the probability of each next state given an action taken from an existing state.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] For instance, the Dyna algorithm learns a model from experience, and uses that to provide more modelled transitions for a value function, in addition to the real transitions.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Such methods can sometimes be extended to use of non-parametric models, such as when the transitions are simply stored and "replayed" to the learning algorithm.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Model-based methods can be more computationally intensive than model-free approaches, and their utility can be limited by the extent to which the Markov decision process can be learnt.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] There are other ways to use models than to update a value function.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] For instance, in model predictive control the model is used to update the behavior directly.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The costly exploration needed to learn an optimal policy can be reduced if some supervised data is available.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This can be achieved for instance by learning a crude control policy and using this to initialize the Q table intelligently instead of with zeros.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Both the asymptotic and finite-sample behaviors of most algorithms are well understood.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Algorithms with provably (i.e. in a way that can be proved) good online performance (addressing the exploration issue) are known.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Efficient exploration of Markov decision processes is given in Burnetas and Katehakis (1997).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Finite-time performance bounds have also appeared for many algorithms, but these bounds are expected to be rather loose and thus more work is needed to better understand the relative advantages and limitations.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] For incremental algorithms, asymptotic convergence issues have been settled.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Temporal-difference-based algorithms converge under a wider set of conditions than was previously possible (for example, when used with arbitrary, smooth function approximation).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Associative reinforcement learning tasks combine facets of stochastic learning automata tasks and supervised learning pattern classification tasks.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In associative reinforcement learning tasks, the learning system interacts in a closed loop with its environment.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This approach extends reinforcement learning by using a deep neural network and without explicitly designing the state space.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The work on learning ATARI games by Google DeepMind increased attention to deep reinforcement learning or end-to-end reinforcement learning.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Adversarial deep reinforcement learning is an active area of research in reinforcement learning focusing on vulnerabilities of learned policies.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In this research area some studies initially showed that reinforcement learning policies are susceptible to imperceptible adversarial manipulations.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] While some methods have been proposed to overcome these susceptibilities, in the most recent studies it has been shown that these proposed solutions are far from providing an accurate representation of current vulnerabilities of deep reinforcement learning policies.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] By introducing fuzzy inference in reinforcement learning, approximating the state-action value function with fuzzy rules in continuous space becomes possible.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The IF - THEN form of fuzzy rules make this approach suitable for expressing the results in a form close to natural language.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Extending FRL with Fuzzy Rule Interpolation allows the use of reduced size sparse fuzzy rule-bases to emphasize cardinal rules (most important state-action values).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In inverse reinforcement learning (IRL), no reward function is given.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Instead, the reward function is inferred given an observed behavior from an expert.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The idea is to mimic observed behavior, which is often optimal or close to optimal.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] One popular IRL paradigm is named maximum entropy inverse reinforcement learning (MaxEnt IRL).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] MaxEnt IRL estimates the parameters of a linear model of the reward function by maximizing the entropy of the probability distribution of observed trajectories subject to constraints related to matching expected feature counts.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Recently it has been shown that MaxEnt IRL is a particular case of a more general framework named random utility inverse reinforcement learning (RU-IRL).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] RU-IRL is based on random utility theory and Markov decision processes.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The utility function is modeled as a random variable to account for the ignorance of the observer regarding the features the observed agent actually considers in its utility function.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Multi-objective reinforcement learning (MORL) is a form of reinforcement learning concerned with conflicting alternatives.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] It is distinct from multi-objective optimization in that it is concerned with agents acting in environments.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Safe reinforcement learning (SRL) can be defined as the process of learning policies that maximize the expectation of the return in problems in which it is important to ensure reasonable system performance and/or respect safety constraints during the learning and/or deployment processes.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] An alternative approach is risk-averse reinforcement learning, where instead of the *expected* return, a *risk-measure* of the return is optimized, such as the conditional value at risk (CVaR).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In addition to mitigating risk, the CVaR objective increases robustness to model uncertainties.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] However, CVaR optimization in risk-averse RL requires special care, to prevent gradient bias and blindness to success.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Self-reinforcement learning (or self-learning), is a learning paradigm which does not use the concept of immediate reward $R_{a}(s,s')$ after transition from s to $s'$ with action a .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] It does not use an external reinforcement, it only uses the agent internal self-reinforcement.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The internal self-reinforcement is provided by mechanism of feelings and emotions.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In the learning process emotions are backpropagated by a mechanism of secondary reinforcement.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The learning equation does not include the immediate reward, it only includes the state evaluation.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Compute state evaluation $v(s')$ of how good it is to be in the consequence situation $s'$ .
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Initial conditions of the memory are received as input from the genetic environment.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] It is a system with only one input (situation), and only one output (action, or behavior).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Self-reinforcement (self-learning) was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-reinforcement learning, named Crossbar Adaptive Array (CAA).
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The CAA computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence states.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Efficient comparison of RL algorithms is essential for research, deployment and monitoring of RL systems.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] To compare different algorithms on a given environment, an agent can be trained for each algorithm.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Since the performance is sensitive to implementation details, all algorithms should be implemented as closely as possible to each other.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] After the training is finished, the agents can be run on a sample of test episodes, and their scores (returns) can be compared.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Since episodes are typically assumed to be i.i.d, standard statistical tools can be used for hypothesis testing, such as T-test and permutation test.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This requires to accumulate all the rewards within an episode into a single number—the episodic return.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] However, this causes a loss of information, as different time-steps are averaged together, possibly with different levels of noise.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Whenever the noise level varies across the episode, the statistical power can be improved significantly, by weighting the rewards according to their estimated noise.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Despite significant advancements, reinforcement learning (RL) continues to face several challenges and limitations that hinder its widespread application in real-world scenarios.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] RL algorithms often require a large number of interactions with the environment to learn effective policies, leading to high computational costs and time-intensive to train the agent.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] For instance, OpenAI's Dota-playing bot utilized thousands of years of simulated gameplay to achieve human-level performance.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Techniques like experience replay and curriculum learning have been proposed to reduce sample inefficiency, but these techniques add more complexity and are not always sufficient for real-world applications.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Training RL models, particularly for deep neural network-based models, can be unstable and prone to divergence.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] A small change in the policy or environment can lead to extreme fluctuations in performance, making it difficult to achieve consistent results.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This instability is further enhanced in the case of the continuous or high-dimensional action space, where the learning step becomes more complex and less predictable.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The RL agents trained in specific environments often struggle to generalize their learned policies to new, unseen scenarios.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This is the major setback preventing the application of RL to dynamic real-world environments where adaptability is crucial.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] The challenge is to develop such algorithms that can transfer knowledge across tasks and environments without extensive retraining.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Designing appropriate reward functions is critical in RL because poorly designed reward functions can lead to unintended behaviors.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In addition, RL systems trained on biased data may perpetuate existing biases and lead to discriminatory or unfair outcomes.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Both of these issues requires careful consideration of reward structures and data sources to ensure fairness and desired behaviors.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] In recent years Since the early 2020s, reinforcement learning has become a significant concept in natural language processing (NLP), where tasks are often sequential decision-making rather than static classification.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning is where an agent take actions in an environment to maximize the accumulation of rewards.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This framework is best fit for many NLP tasks, including dialogue generation, text summarization, and machine translation, where the quality of the output depends on optimizing long-term or human-centered goals rather than the prediction of single correct label.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Early application of RL in NLP emerged in dialogue systems, where conversation was determined as a series of actions optimized for fluency and coherence.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] These early attempts, including policy gradient and sequence-level training techniques, laid a foundation for the broader application of reinforcement learning to other areas of NLP.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] A major breakthrough happened with the introduction of reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), a method in which human feedback ratings are used to train a reward model that guides the RL agent.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] Unlike traditional rule-based or supervised systems, RLHF allows models to align their behavior with human judgments on complex and subjective tasks.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This technique was initially used in the development of InstructGPT, an effective language model trained to follow human instructions and later in ChatGPT which incorporates RLHF for improving output responses and ensuring safety.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] More recently, researchers have explored the use of offline RL in NLP to improve dialogue systems without the need of live human interaction.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] These methods optimize for user engagement, coherence, and diversity based on past conversation logs and pre-trained reward models.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] One example is DeepSeek-R1, which incorporates multi-stage training and cold-start data before RL.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] DeepSeek-R1 achieves performance comparable to OpenAI-o1-1217 on reasoning tasks.
[src:rlhf/reinforcement-learning] This model was trained via large-scale RL without supervised fine-tuning (SFT) as a preliminary step.
